diff:1612512844:1612416492:=65,86d64%0a%3c #foxbegin 210205-081404-31000#%0a%3c (:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c [-05.02.2021 - 00:14-] &nbsp; %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 210205-081404-31000 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c !!!!!JoshuaC%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c '''Developing the instinct'''%0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c%0a%3c You raise a very interesting question about how the instinct to put adjectives in a certain order is developed, given that some native English speakers are not even aware that such a rule exists. %0a%3c %0a%3c One possible explanation could be that the instinct was developed due to long term exposure to and experience with the English language. For example, an English speaker would probably have a more visceral reaction to the phrase "the bad big wolf" as compared to the phrase "a yellow old trumpet", given that the "big bad wolf" is a more common phrase than "an old yellow trumpet".%0a%3c %0a%3c However, this may not explain the phenomenon fully. It is impossible for us to have heard every single combination of adjectives, but we often have a gut feeling when we see or hear adjectives written in the wrong order. Did we subconsciously group certain adjectives together and somehow derive the rules ourselves? %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210205-081404-31000#%0a
